  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `geth version`\r\n1.6.7\r\nOS & Version: Windows/Linux/OSX\r\nLinux\r\nCommit hash : (if `develop`)\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nI was trying to measure transaction processing time under different network configurations on a private ethereum blockchain (we have 10 miners and 10 clients implemented on Openstack vms, each of them is manually connected with all other peers), but encountered something unexpected. \r\n\r\nWe managed to send transactions at around 25 tps for about 30 min with the default block size. As transactions are issued periodically, we expect them to be uniformly distributed among blocks, and block sizes to be roughly the same. \r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nThe result was a bit shocking: we received several blocks with ~5000 transactions in them, and between two big blocks there are always several empty blocks. \r\n\r\nI then tried to limit the block size by setting the gasLimit tag, but after that there were more invalid transactions. \r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\n````\r\n[backtrace]\r\n````",
